Phil Spitalny (November 7, 1890 – October 11, 1970) was a Ukrainian-American musician, music critic, composer, and bandleader heard often on radio during the 1930s and 1940s.
A child prodigy on clarinet, he toured Russia and came to the United States in 1905.
For two years, he conducted the orchestra at the Stanley Theatre in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
He led orchestras under the name Phil Spitalny and His All-Girl Orchestra, beginning with Hour of Charm Orchestra on his radio program The Hour of Charm in 1934.

He led orchestras under the name Phil Spitalny and His All-Girl Orchestra, beginning with Hour of Charm Orchestra on his radio program The Hour of Charm in 1934.
The program lasted for over ten years on radio.
The orchestra made a guest appearance in the Abbott and Costello movie Here Come the Co-Eds in 1945.
Spitalny also appeared in When Johnny Comes Marching Home (1942) and on Ed Sullivan's television program Toast of the Town.
He died of cancer in Miami Beach in 1970 at the age of 79.
